{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22281"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22281"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.32,0.09,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108136"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90548"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12955"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43767"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108136"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine follow-up of her chronic kidney disease. She was diagnosed with stage 3a chronic kidney disease two years ago. Her medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes diagnosed eight years ago. Her current medications include metformin 1000 mg twice daily, gliclazide MR 60 mg daily, perindopril 5 mg daily, and atorvastatin 20 mg daily. She works as a teacher and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 138/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 9.2 mmol/L (2.5-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 118 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate 45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin:creatinine ratio 45 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in managing her albuminuria?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitor","Increase perindopril to 10 mg daily","Add spironolactone 25 mg daily","Refer for renal biopsy","Add candesartan 8 mg daily"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has stage 3a chronic kidney disease with persistent macroalbuminuria (urine albumin:creatinine ratio 45 mg/mmol) despite being on a submaximal dose of an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor. The most appropriate next step is to optimise her current therapy before adding additional agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing perindopril to 10 mg daily\u003C/strong\u003E follows evidence-based guidelines for managing persistent albuminuria. ACE inhibitors should be titrated to the maximum tolerated dose before considering additional agents. This approach maximises the renoprotective effects of ACE inhibition, which include reducing intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria. During this it is important to monitor for potential side effects such as hypotension and hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdding spironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E may have additional benefits in reducing proteinuria, but should only be considered after maximising the dose of an ACE inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker (ARB). Adding spironolactone may also increase risk of hyperkalaemia, particularly in patients with reduced kidney function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdding candesartan\u003C/strong\u003E (an ARB) to an ACE inhibitor is not recommended as first-line therapy for albuminuria. Dual blockade of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system with an ACE inhibitor and ARB combination increases the risk of hyperkalaemia and acute kidney injury without providing substantial additional benefit for most patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered in this patient with type 2 diabetes and chronic kidney disease, as these medications have shown renoprotective effects. However, current CKD guidelines still recommend optimising ACE inhibitor or ARB therapy first before adding other agents for albuminuria management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for renal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. The patient has a clear cause for her kidney disease (diabetes and hypertension), and her presentation is consistent with diabetic kidney disease. Renal biopsy could be considered if there were features suggesting an alternative diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPersistent albuminuria is a marker of kidney damage and an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease and progression of kidney disease. The goal of therapy is to reduce albuminuria to the lowest possible level, which often requires a multifaceted approach including optimal blood pressure control, glycaemic control, and specific renoprotective medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ACE inhibitors and ARBs should be titrated to maximum tolerated doses before adding a second agent for albuminuria management.","Monitoring for hypotension and hyperkalaemia is essential when up-titrating ACE inhibitors or ARBs.","Persistent albuminuria is a marker of kidney damage and an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90548"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22281"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90548"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-07T09:05:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-07T18:26:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15246"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://